{
  "What does Hooke's Law describe?": "",
  "The relationship between spring force and extension": "",
  "The relationship between mass and gravitational force": "",
  "The relationship between friction and surface area": "",
  "The relationship between pressure and temperature": "",
  "Hooke's Law states that the force exerted by a spring is directly proportional to its extension or compression, as long as the elastic limit is not exceeded. The formula is F = kx.": "",
  "In the formula F = kx, what does 'k' represent?": "",
  "The mass of the object on the spring": "",
  "The spring constant (stiffness of the spring)": "",
  "The length of the entire spring at rest": "",
  "The gravitational acceleration at that spot": "",
  "In F = kx, 'k' is the spring constant, which measures the stiffness of the spring. A larger k means a stiffer spring that requires more force to stretch or compress by the same amount.": "",
  "In the formula F = kx, what does 'x' represent?": "",
  "The original length of the spring at rest": "",
  "The mass hanging from the spring below": "",
  "The extension or compression of the spring": "",
  "The speed of the spring when it bounces": "",
  "In F = kx, 'x' is the displacement of the spring from its natural (resting) length. It can be either an extension (stretching) or a compression (squeezing), measured in meters.": "",
  "What unit is the spring constant (k) measured in?": "",
  "Kilograms per meter": "",
  "Meters per second squared": "",
  "Newtons per meter (N/m)": "",
  "Joules per kilogram value": "",
  "The spring constant k is measured in newtons per meter (N/m). It tells you how many newtons of force are needed to stretch or compress the spring by one meter.": "",
  "If you double the extension of a spring (within elastic limit), what happens to the force?": "",
  "The force doubles as well for that spring": "",
  "The force stays the same as before always": "",
  "The force is cut in half from before": "",
  "The force quadruples from the original value": "",
  "Hooke's Law (F = kx) shows a direct proportion: if you double x, the force F also doubles. This linear relationship holds as long as the spring is not stretched past its elastic limit.": "",
  "What is the elastic limit of a spring?": "",
  "The point at which the spring cannot return to its original shape": "",
  "The maximum speed the spring can reach when released from rest": "",
  "The resting length of the spring when no force is applied to it": "",
  "The temperature at which the spring melts into liquid metal form": "",
  "The elastic limit is the maximum extension or compression a spring can undergo while still returning to its original shape. Beyond this point, the spring is permanently deformed and Hooke's Law no longer applies.": "",
  "A spring with k = 100 N/m is stretched 0.2 m. What force does it exert?": "",
  "500 newtons of force": "",
  "20 newtons of force": "",
  "0.002 newtons of force": "",
  "200 newtons of force": "",
  "Using F = kx: F = 100 N/m x 0.2 m = 20 N. The spring exerts a restoring force of 20 newtons, pulling back toward its natural length.": "",
  "What direction does the spring force act?": "",
  "In the same direction as the stretch or compression": "",
  "Always pointing straight downward toward the Earth": "",
  "Opposite to the direction of stretch or compression": "",
  "In a random direction each time it is stretched": "",
  "The spring force (restoring force) always acts opposite to the direction of displacement. If you stretch a spring to the right, it pulls back to the left. If compressed, it pushes back outward.": "",
  "Which spring is stiffer: one with k = 50 N/m or one with k = 200 N/m?": "",
  "The spring with k = 50 N/m is stiffer": "",
  "Both springs are equally stiff overall": "",
  "The spring with k = 200 N/m is stiffer": "",
  "Stiffness cannot be determined from k": "",
  "A higher spring constant means a stiffer spring. k = 200 N/m requires 200 N to stretch it by 1 meter, while k = 50 N/m only needs 50 N. The 200 N/m spring is four times stiffer.": "",
  "Can Hooke's Law apply to compressing a spring as well as stretching it?": "",
  "No, it only applies to stretching springs out": "",
  "Yes, it applies to both stretching and compressing": "",
  "No, compressed springs follow different laws": "",
  "Yes, but only for very large compressions here": "",
  "Hooke's Law applies equally to both extension (stretching) and compression (squeezing) of a spring, as long as the elastic limit is not exceeded. F = kx works for both cases.": "",
  "What is Hooke's Law?": "",
  "The law stating spring force is proportional to displacement": "",
  "The law stating objects at rest stay at rest without force": "",
  "The law stating every action has an equal opposite reaction": "",
  "The law stating energy cannot be created or destroyed ever": "",
  "Hooke's Law states that the force needed to extend or compress a spring is directly proportional to the distance of extension or compression. The formula F = kx expresses this relationship mathematically.": "",
  "What does 'spring constant' mean?": "",
  "A measure of how stiff or resistant a spring is to deformation": "",
  "The natural resting length of a spring with no force applied": "",
  "The maximum weight a spring can hold before breaking apart": "",
  "The speed at which a spring bounces back to original shape": "",
  "The spring constant (k) measures the stiffness of a spring. A higher k value means the spring is harder to stretch or compress. It is measured in newtons per meter (N/m).": "",
  "What does 'elastic' mean in the context of springs?": "",
  "Able to return to original shape after being deformed": "",
  "Permanently changed in shape after being deformed": "",
  "Unable to be stretched or compressed at all here": "",
  "Made of rubber material only for this purpose": "",
  "Elastic means the material can return to its original shape after the force is removed. Springs are elastic within their elastic limit. Beyond that, they become permanently deformed (plastic deformation).": "",
  "What does 'restoring force' mean?": "",
  "The force that pushes a spring back to its natural length": "",
  "The force that stretches a spring beyond its elastic limit": "",
  "The gravitational force acting on the spring and mass": "",
  "The friction force between the spring and the surface": "",
  "The restoring force is the force a spring exerts to return to its equilibrium (natural) position. It always points toward the equilibrium, opposing the displacement that caused it.": "",
  "What does 'extension' mean for a spring?": "",
  "How much longer the spring is compared to its natural length": "",
  "The total length of the spring when nothing is attached": "",
  "The maximum force the spring can exert when stretched": "",
  "The stiffness of the spring measured in newtons per meter": "",
  "Extension is the amount a spring has been stretched beyond its natural (resting) length. If a spring's natural length is 10 cm and it is stretched to 15 cm, the extension is 5 cm.": "",
  "What does 'compression' mean for a spring?": "",
  "Stretching the spring longer than its natural length": "",
  "Squeezing the spring shorter than its natural length": "",
  "Breaking the spring into two separate pieces": "",
  "Keeping the spring at exactly its resting length": "",
  "Compression is when a spring is pushed shorter than its natural length. The compressed spring pushes back outward with a restoring force proportional to the amount of compression.": "",
  "What is meant by 'equilibrium position' for a spring?": "",
  "The natural resting position where the spring exerts no force": "",
  "The maximum stretch point where force is greatest on it": "",
  "The position where the spring is fully compressed down": "",
  "The point where the spring breaks apart permanently": "",
  "The equilibrium position is where the spring is at its natural length and exerts no force. When displaced from equilibrium, the restoring force pulls or pushes the spring back toward this position.": "",
  "What does 'directly proportional' mean in Hooke's Law?": "",
  "As one quantity doubles the other one doubles too": "",
  "As one quantity doubles the other is cut in half": "",
  "Both quantities always remain exactly the same": "",
  "The two quantities have no relationship at all": "",
  "Directly proportional means when one quantity increases, the other increases by the same factor. In F = kx, if x doubles, F doubles. If x triples, F triples. They change together in the same ratio.": "",
  "What does 'deformation' mean?": "",
  "A change in the shape or size of an object due to force": "",
  "The natural resting shape of an object with no forces": "",
  "The color change that occurs when stretching a spring": "",
  "The temperature increase in a spring during stretching": "",
  "Deformation is a change in the shape or size of an object caused by an applied force. Elastic deformation is temporary (object returns to shape), while plastic deformation is permanent.": "",
  "What does 'elastic potential energy' mean?": "",
  "Energy stored in a stretched or compressed spring": "",
  "Energy of a moving object due to its velocity": "",
  "Energy stored due to an object's height above ground": "",
  "Energy transferred as heat between two objects": "",
  "Elastic potential energy is the energy stored in a spring (or any elastic object) when it is stretched or compressed. When released, this stored energy can be converted into kinetic energy.": "",
